Q1. What is JavaScript?
-------------------------
JavaScript is a programming language used to make web pages interactive and dynamic.
With JavaScript you can:
Show alerts
Validate forms
Change webpage content
Create animations
Handle button clicks
It works mainly inside the browser.
Example
alert("Hello Mahesh!");
This will show a popup message in the browser.
Another Example
let name = "Mahesh";
console.log(name);
Output in console:
Mahesh
Q2. What are data types in JavaScript? What are primitive data types?
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Data Types
Data types define what kind of data a variable can store.
Example:
Number
Text
True/False
Object
Example code:
let age = 25;       // Number
let name = "Mahesh"; // String
let isActive = true; // Boolean
Primitive Data Types
Primitive data types store single simple values.
There are 7 primitive data types in JavaScript:
String – text
Number – numeric value
Boolean – true or false
Undefined – variable declared but not assigned
Null – empty value
BigInt – very large numbers
Symbol – unique identifier
Example
let name = "Mahesh";    // String
let age = 25;           // Number
let isStudent = true;   // Boolean
let city;               // Undefined
let data = null;        // Null
Q3. Difference between Primitive and Non-Primitive Data Types
-----------------------------------------------------------
Primitive Data Types ==>	Non-Primitive Data Types
Store single value ==>	Store multiple values
Simple data	==>Complex data
Immutable ==>	Mutable
Stored directly in memory ==>	Stored by reference
Primitive Example
let a = 10;
let b = a;
b = 20;
console.log(a); // 10
console.log(b); // 20
Here a does not change.
Non-Primitive Example
let obj1 = {name: "Mahesh"};
let obj2 = obj1;
obj2.name = "Rahul";
console.log(obj1.name); // Rahul
Here both objects change because they reference the same memory.
Q4. What are Arrays, Functions and Objects?
--------------------------------------------------
1. Array
An array stores multiple values in a single variable.
Example
let fruits = ["Apple", "Mango", "Banana"];
console.log(fruits[0]);
Output
Apple
2. Function
A function is a block of code that performs a specific task.
Example
function greet() {
  console.log("Hello Mahesh");
}
greet();
Output
Hello Mahesh
Function with parameters
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}
console.log(add(5, 3));
Output
8
3. Object
An object stores data in key-value pairs.
Example
let person = {
  name: "Mahesh",
  age: 25,
  city: "Mumbai"
};
console.log(person.name);
Output
Mahesh
Q5. What is Scope in JavaScript?
--------------------------------
Scope defines where a variable can be accessed in the program.
There are 3 types of scope:
Global Scope
Function Scope
Block Scope
1. Global Scope
Variable declared outside a function.
let name = "Mahesh";
function show() {
  console.log(name);
}
show();
Accessible everywhere.
2. Function Scope
Variable declared inside a function.
function test() {
  let age = 25;
  console.log(age);
}
test();
age cannot be accessed outside the function.
3. Block Scope
Variables declared with let or const inside {}
{
  let city = "Mumbai";
  console.log(city);
}
city cannot be used outside the block.

Q6. What is the difference between var, let, and const in JavaScript?
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
These are used to declare variables.
Feature	var =	let	= const
Re-declare	✅ Allowed =	❌ Not allowed =	❌ Not allowed
Reassign value 	✅ Yes	= ✅ Yes	= ❌ No
Scope	Function scope =	Block scope =	Block scope
Preferred in modern JS	❌ =	✅ =	✅
1️⃣ var Example
var name = "Mahesh";
var name = "Rahul";   // allowed
console.log(name);
Output
Rahul
2️⃣ let Example
let age = 25;
age = 30;   // allowed
console.log(age);
Output
30
But redeclaration is not allowed:
let age = 25;
let age = 30; // Error
3️⃣ const Example
const value cannot be changed.
const city = "Mumbai";
city = "Delhi"; // Error
Q7. What is a Loop? What are the types of loops in JavaScript?
----------------------------------------------------------------
A loop is used to repeat a block of code multiple times.
Example: Print numbers from 1 to 5.
Types of loops in JavaScript
for loop
while loop
do...while loop
for...in loop
for...of loop
Example of loop
for(let i = 1; i <= 5; i++){
  console.log(i);
}
Output
1
2
3
4
5
Q8. Difference between for, while, and do-while loop
---------------------------------------------------
Loop	= Condition Check	= Use
for	 = Before execution	= When number of iterations is known
while =	Before execution	= When condition based loop
do-while =	After execution = 	Runs at least once
1️⃣ for loop
for(let i = 1; i <= 3; i++){
  console.log(i);
}
Output
1
2
3
2️⃣ while loop
let i = 1;
while(i <= 3){
  console.log(i);
  i++;
}
3️⃣ do...while loop
let i = 1;
do{
  console.log(i);
  i++;
}while(i <= 3);
The do-while loop runs at least once even if condition is false.
Q9. Difference between for...of and for...in loop
-----------------------------------------------------
Loop =	Used For =	Returns
for...of =	Arrays, Strings =	Values
for...in  = 	Objects =	Keys
for...of Example
let fruits = ["Apple", "Mango", "Banana"];
for(let fruit of fruits){
  console.log(fruit);
}
Output
Apple
Mango
Banana
for...in Example
let person = {
  name: "Mahesh",
  age: 25
};
for(let key in person){
  console.log(key);
}
Output
name
age
Q10. What is forEach() method? Compare it with for...of and for...in.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
forEach() is an array method used to loop through array elements.
forEach Example
let numbers = [1,2,3];
numbers.forEach(function(num){
  console.log(num);
});
Output
1
2
3
Comparison
Feature	forEach	for...of	for...in
Works with array	✅	✅	❌
Works with object	❌	❌	✅
Returns value	Element	Element	Key
Break/Continue	❌ Not allowed	✅ Allowed	✅ Allowed
Q11. Difference between == and === in JavaScript?
---------------------------------------------------
Operator	Name	Checks
==	Loose equality	Value only
===	Strict equality	Value + Type
== Example
console.log(5 == "5");
Output
true
Because type conversion happens.
=== Example
console.log(5 === "5");
Output
false
Because:
Number ≠ String
✅ Simple Rule
==   → checks value
===  → checks value + datatype
Most developers prefer ===.
